The report comes in the wake of an announcement on Wednesday by Health Chief Administrative Secretary Mercy Mwangangi that teachers would be among those to be vaccinated against the coronavirus, alongside health workers and police officers.
“Teachers are frontline workers and will receive vaccines once we roll them out,” said Dr Mwangangi.
Covid-19 infections have started rising, with the Health ministry yesterday announcing one death and 230 more infections, bringing the total to 98, 184.





The TSC is worried that the reopening of schools makes them potential super-spreaders and would, therefore, ensure that tutors are safe.
Chief executive Nancy Macharia said all efforts are being made to ensure that teachers currently under medical attention receive the best care “so they return to their full health and resume normal services of attending to learners”.
Ms Macharia said the TSC is also working with other stakeholders to ensure the wellbeing of teachers and measures are in place to ensure their safety.
Kenya has 337,432 teachers serving in more than 30,000 public primary and post-primary schools.
Ms Macharia said the commission had negotiated with the medical insurance provider Minet to cover all teachers who may suffer from the virus.



