Field officers
“The commission’s field officers are also working with stakeholders in the health sector to provide psycho-social support to all teachers who may require the service,” she said.
Ms Macharia advised teachers aged 58 and above to work from home as directed by President Uhuru Kenyatta.
She said even though the Education ministry has not issued a circular to implement the directive, the TSC would not sack any teacher with underlying conditions for working from home.
There are more than 25,000 teachers aged over 58.
Ms Macharia said the TSC had put in place measures to protect teachers from Covid 19 in conjunction with the Health ministry and counties.
Meanwhile, the Unicef has asked schools to observe Covid-19 health protocols to curb the spread of coronavirus.
Chief of Education Kenya, Marilyn Hoar, said the health guidelines are global safety precautions issued by the World Health Organisations, which are key to keeping children safe in schools.
“Unicef welcomes the reopening of schools in Kenya, our call for schools is to do everything possible to ensure children are not infected,” said Dr Hoar.
The Unicef call comes even as it emerged many learning institutions, especially public schools, are congested despite a requirement to observe 1.5 metres social distancing in classes.



