Dr Hoar said schools must be safe. She asked learners, teachers and other staff to observe the social distancing whenever possible, wash hands with soap and water, ensure free circulation of air and wear clean facemasks in schools and public spaces.
  Community spread
She said research had shown that the transmission rate among children is lower than adults and asked parents to educate their children on hygiene.
“To prevent community spread of the Covid-19 to schools, parents must ensure they observe the best hygiene at home. They are also supposed to be on the forefront in ensuring children learn to observe the health protocols,” said Dr Hoar.
She added that children are safer in schools than at home and asked parents to ensure their children resume studies.
She warned that the longer children stay at home, the more they risk developing mental problems.
Dr Hoar said the Unicef is working with the State support to teachers and learners.
“With the reopening of schools, there is a lot of anxiety among parents and learners. However, we have been working with TSC to train teachers on mental health and how to handle learners when they resume school,” she said.
